jobDescription: Developing the next generation cloud-based SD-WAN enterprise solutions product with a centrally managed network connections tool, providing a simple and reliable solution to the complexity of managing distributed network system.
jobDescription2:
•	Developed an Apache Kafka GUI using Admin API and ProcessBuilder API that enables users to seamlessly start a Kafka cluster with Zookeeper and brokers with intuitive UI and simple configurations that replaces convoluted setup process that involves complex manual configurations and spinning up of multiple servers through terminal windows.
•	Architected a Java backend with fast and reliable integration with Kafka cluster enabled by Kafka’s native Java APIs which allow cluster health monitoring and configurations with the advantages of OOP paradigm with modularity and reusability optimal for efficient troubleshooting and debugging in accordance of DRY principle.
•	Leveraged Spring Boot library in building RESTful API server with loosely coupled controller and model layers enabled by IoC and optimized readability by annotation dependency injections in line with Kafka’s scalable nature.
•	Designed and developed a single-page application with React Hooks using functional components that provide modularity and maintainability with internal state management for local data cache and uninterrupted user interactivity.
•	Applied TypeScript and interface-oriented developing for scalability by ensuring type consistency which improved readability between developers, and enhanced sustainability by compile-time error handling to reduce run-time errors.
•	Employed JUnit for unit testing to verify code validity and prevent unintended consequences from modules by mocking dependencies.
•	Assembled the request endpoints with WebSocket to automate Kafka cluster throughput monitoring by creating a persistent bidirectional TCP channel to feed the dashboard with updates to the cluster for real-time visualization of cluster health.
•	Accelerated at OS Labs

description:
Hello! My name is Ashia (eye-sha) Nagi and I am a Yemeni American who immigrated to America at a young age. Fall 2019, I graduated with a Bachelor of Science in Applied Mathematics and a minor in Sociology. My interests are product management, data science, and software engineering. 

In 2017, I participated in the biggest tech/business competition at City College of New York (CCNY) where my team, PaxWalk, won the Standard Chartered Bank grand prize. PaxWalk is a safety app that helps college students find walking buddies. I was also selected to be part of Code/Interactive Tech Career Accelerator Program (TCAP), which is a 2-year mentorship and career development program for high potential students. 
 
During my senior year, I was the Social Media Coordinator in the Society of Women Engineers Club where I successfully raised awareness of SWE to improve support among women engineers at CCNY. I also taught an iOS CodePath course to CCNY students in order to build 7 mini-applications. 

In Summer 2019, I've joined QCC Techworks Coding Bootcamp to further my knowledge in SQL, MongoDB, Reactjs, and Javascript. My personal passion is to inspire other immigrant students to follow their dreams. I am doing that by posting weekly videos about college/career tips on my Youtube channel.

description:
I'm a Software Developer at SAP Labs under their SAP Next Talent(SNT) Program, formally known as Silicon Valley Next Talent(SVNT) Program, and have been under contract for a year now. The SNT Program is an 18-month rotational program where I can work on different teams and technologies on each rotation. I'm a graduate from the University at Buffalo, School of Engineering and Applied Science with a Bachelor of Science in Computer Science. I am also a Bootcamp graduate from Fullstack Academy, based in New York City.

Currently, I am doing my second rotation on the Concur Data Plane - Business Intelligence team, where I recently had the opportunity to develop a Redshift Cluster Toggle to facilitate Redshift clusters' scheduling. The business justification for the toggle is to lower the team's incurring charges for on-demand resources by automating the pausing and resuming of clusters.

I worked on the SAP Conversational AI - Connect team in my first rotation, where I implemented many front-end and back-end features for the Slack, Facebook Messenger, Microsoft Teams, and LINE channels. One of the projects I had a significant impact was the migration from the Attachments API to the Block Kit API for our Slack channel. I delivered the Proof of Concept for the project, which helped the team measure the feasibility of the task.

During my time at the University at Buffalo, I participated at my University's Nano-Satellite Laboratory, a group of students that work on satellite contracts obtained from the Air Force Research Lab, NASA, and Moog. While at the laboratory, I had the opportunity to work on the GLADOS satellite, where I improved the magnetometer and worked on improving the gyroscope. 

I attended and completed Full Stack Academy while finishing my Bachelor's degree and have gone back to mentor recent Bootcamp graduates by providing mock technical interviews via white-boarding, pair programming, and code reviews. I've also offered 1:1 check-ins to set mentee goals, weekly job search schedules and discuss blockers via follow-up calls or texts.

description:
I am a software engineer on the Google News team, based in the New York office. I am an alumnus of Harvard College (class of 2020), with a Bachelor of Arts degree in Computer Science and Statistics (joint) and a secondary field of African American Studies.

My experience and passions range from Computer Science and other scientific research to social justice and non-profit impact work. I have explored each of these passions extensively, with my most recent project being my undergraduate thesis, which uses CS and statistics to combat racial gerrymandering in the US. I maintain a scholarly interest, and tangible skills, in many other areas, ranging from theoretical and applied statistics to social sciences like Economics and African American Studies.

I devote my extra time to service, event planning, community organizing, intellectual discussion, and artistic expression through photography and filmmaking. I am eager to pursue new opportunities for creative and professional growth, and to support young Black technologists and artists.

description:
I’m a full stack Ruby on Rails engineer with a background in math, physics, and K-8 technology education. I’m a big proponent of test-driven development, pair programming, and continuous integration, and I believe that clear, well written code with solid test coverage is the key to high quality maintainable code that I—and my colleagues—won’t regret six months, or six years, from now.

As a student of physics, one of our most important problem-solving techniques was learning how to take difficult, complicated problems, break them into simple, easily solved subcomponents, rigorously solve each piece, and then compose them back together to form more powerful, general purpose solutions. So long as you don’t assume all cows are perfectly spherically symmetric, that is. I find this approach equally valid in software.

I’ve been programming in one way or another for over twenty years, from writing MS-DOS startup scripts (to optimize memory for Wing Commander, X-Wing, and other games, naturally), learning HTML in 1995, or writing programs in Fortran and MatLab during my physics curriculum. 2001 was my Year-of-the-Linux-Desktop (I’m a Gentoo guy), but I’ve always believed in the right tool for the right job and

description:
While studying Psychology in college, I had a low-end laptop that seemed to fail me each time an important assignment was due. Chronic frustration grew to curiosity, and I found myself glued to the computer researching to build my own PC. This introduced me to the world of tech, and before I knew it, I was learning HTML while working as a Kitchen Assistant. Five years in the unpredictable and fast-paced catering business helped me easily develop trust with teammates, leading to effective and efficient collaboration that always results in events that clients love.

Since I have transitioned to a Web Developer, my priority is still building products that create experiences that users love. I have developed three apps (check them out below!), and I am currently working on a web app to help users document their gardens. Here are my favorites: 

WavesOn - Marine weather tracking app with a journalling feature, this was a real passion project for me because it enabled me to finally build out a way to check marine weather before going to the beach! I have this hosted on heroku, linked below under Featured, and Projects tabs! Check it out and please message me for any feedback!

_explore_ - A call to explore our solar system using NASA’s photo of the day, and Le Systeme Solaire API for pulling data on our neighboring celestial objects. This is a work in progress, but I have my Github repo link below!

SKINN - Skincare customizer with review functionality to help women find top performing natural products. Demo link included below under projects!

I am open to more opportunities to build, particularly products that provide time-saving solutions.  If you know of any, feel free to send them my way. I can be reached via LinkedIn DM, or feel free to email me at cbatsoula@gmail.com.

description:
Growing up, I always wanted to be an artist. It wasn't long, however, before I realized I lacked any natural affinity for drawing, painting, or sculpting. Thus, I lost sight of my creative passion and pursued what I was good at: logic, problem-solving, and analysis. By the time I graduated, I found myself wanting more for my future. I wanted to take the analytical skills I'd honed during my academic career and use them in a more creative and challenging way. 

Although environmental policy and web development might seem to have little in common, their core principle - and fittingly, Dev Bootcamp's mantra - is the same: make beautiful and (more importantly) meaningful things. Such a slogan struck a chord in me the moment I saw it printed on Dev Bootcamp's walls because what I am most passionate about is progress. I thrive in fast-paced, collaborative environments where positive impact is expected. My goals are firstly, to make a difference no matter how small that difference may be, and secondly, to never stop working towards further personal growth.

Currently I am searching for entry-level opportunities in creative and collaborative work environments, particularly in media, entertainment, and fashion, that allow me to continue my programming education by gaining hands-on experience.
